reviewText: WWF Unforgiven 1999 had six title matches.  The main event was the first ever six pack match for the vacant WWF Championship.  The participants were HHH, Kane, Mankind, The Rock, The Big Show, and The British Bulldog.  The  special enforcer for this match was former champ Stone Cold Steve Austin.  The first ever inter-gender WWF Intercontinental Title match took place as  Champion-Jeff Jarrett defends his belt against Challenger-Chyna.  WWF Tag  Team Champions-New Age Outlaws vs. Challengers-Edge and Christian.  WWF  European Champion-Mark Henry vs. Challenger and former friend-D-Lo Brown.  WWF Women's Champion-Ivory goes up against Challenger-Luna in a hardcore  match.  The WWF Hardcore Championship is on the line in a "Kennel From  Hell" match as Champion-Al Snow takes on Challenger-Big Boss Man.  Also included, Val Venis vs. Steve Blackman.  The Acolytes vs. The Dudley  Boyz.  "Y2J" Chris Jericho goes one on one with X-Pac.
Title: N/A

reviewText: I don't know what that guy who gave this tape five stars is on, but I'd like some of it. Anything that makes this event seem watchable can't be a bad thing. Unforgiven was the worst American WWF pay-per-view of 1999.  Top-liner aside, there wasn't a strong bout in site. For the record, here's  what's on offer...Val Venis faced Steve Blackman in a boring match, D-Lo  brown took on Euro champ Mark Henry in a poor bout, Jeff Jarrett defended  the I.C. strap against Chyna in a fair match, The Acolytes tangled with The  Dudley Boyz in a lame brawl, Ivory retained her Women's title against Luna  in a pathetic 'hardcore' match, World tag champs The New Age Outlaws locked  horns with Edge and Christian in a disappointing bout, Al Snow faced The  Big Bossman in an atrocious 'Kennel From Hell' match (which was, by far,  the worst WWF match of 1999), Chris Jericho took on X-Pac in a huge  let-down and in the main event, Triple H lifted the vacant WWF World title  in a 'Six Pack match' with The Rock, Paul Wight, Davey Boy Smith, Kane and  Mankind.Avoid this tape like the plague.

reviewText: Val Venis vs Steve BlackmanVery boring match. Val wins with money shot. Barely watchable.Rating: 5/10WWF European TitleMark Henry (C) vs D'Lo BrownReally stupid match too. D'Lo wins title after about 5 minutes.Rating: 6/10WWF Intercontinential TitleJeff Jarrett (C) vs ChynaReally entertaining. Chyna is a really good wrestler and she proved it in this match. Jeff Jarrett wins after a reverse decision.Rating: 8/10The Acolytes vs Dudley BoyzGood match. Basically a filler match. Acolytes win after help from Steven Richards.Rating: 7/10WWF Women's TitleHardcore RulesIvory (C) vs LunaNot exactly great, but watchable. Ivory wins.Rating: 7/10WWF Tag Team TitlesNew Age Outlaws (C) vs Edge and ChristianGreat match. One of the highlights of the show. Outlaws win in a long match.Rating: 8/10WWF Hardcore TitleKennel From Hell MatchAl Snow (C) vs Big Boss ManThis match had SO much potential. Could of been way better, but Boss Man always screws up in these situations. Al Snow wins in the end.Rating: 7/10X-Pac vs Chris JerichoFirst PPV for Y2J. Had a pretty good match. X-Pac wins by DQ.Rating: 7/106-Pack Challenge for WWF ChampionshipThe Rock vs Triple H vs British Bulldog vs Kane vs Undertaker vs Mankind vs Big ShowSpecial Enforcer-Stone ColdGreat main event. British Bulldog takes one of the nastiest chair shots i have ever seen. Triple H wins in the end and Stone Cold had to count! Great match from start to finish.Rating: 8/10WWF Unforgiven was a pretty good PPV. The beginning was very bad and should of been cut out of the PPV entirely. The rest was pretty good. Any collector should own this tape.Overall Rating: 75/100

reviewText: Unforgiven was a bad PPV. The main event sucked big time! But there were 3 good matches.1 D'Lo Brown VS Mark Henry: Exciting to see these former friends give everything they got in this match. It didn't bore me 1 second. Best match of the PPV.2 Edge & Christian VS New Age Outlaws: Good Tag team title match. It gets a little boring, but still a good match, save the ending.3 Y2J VS X-Pac: another good match, but just like the tag match, the ending suckes.The worst matches:1 Al Snow VS Bossman: What a dum match. On paper it did look interesting, but in reality it was the worst match of 1999.2 6-pack challenge: It wasn't really bad, but from what I expected, it was a little too less hardcore.

reviewText: This PPv is easily the worst PPV in WWF in 1999. All the matches were 1-star, apart from the 6-pack match which might JUST deserve a 2-star, and the Kennel from Hell match, which gets 0 stars, being the worst wrestling  match I have EVER seen.DO NOT get this tape, instead buy a good PPv,  like Royal Rumble 2000, or No way Out.
